df_span = pd.melt(df_span, id_vars=['pp'], value_vars=['fds', 'bds'], var_name='task', value_name='span')
df_reading = pd.read_csv('data/tamil_reading.tsv', sep='\t')
df_span = df_span.merge(df_reading, left_on='pp', right_on='pp')

# standardize variables
df_span['span_z'] = pmu.standardize(df_span['span'])
df_span['reading_z'] = pmu.standardize(df_span['word'])
df_span['task_binary'] = pd.get_dummies(df_span['task'])['fds']
df_span['task_z'] = pmu.standardize(df_span['task_binary'])

Modeling

First we will set some parameters for the regression procedure, as outlined in the paper.

In [4]:
# default model params
defaults = {
    'samples': 5000,
    'tune': 2000,
    'chains': 4,
    'init': 'advi+adapt_diag',
    'priors': {'fixed': 'narrow', 'random': 'narrow'},
}

We will compare the two models that work in the context of our multilevel model setup:

  1. A null model, with only an overall intercept and by-participant intercepts
  2. A task model, with an additional predictor for task type (fds versus bds)
In [5]:
# null model
model_span_intercept = Model(df_span)
model_span_intercept.fit('span_z ~ 1',
                         random=['1|pp'],
                         **defaults)

The null model throws some warnings. Three divergences and between 10% and 25% effective samples for some parameters is not ideal. Obviously the null model is not our best-guess model in this case, and it will prove clearly inferior in the model comparison reported below, so it is not a big concern.
Sampling for the task model did not yield any warnings, and we will examine some sampling statistics to make sure sampling went well:

r r^ values look good, as does the number of effective samples for the by-participant intercepts. For the overall intercept we have more than 8K effective samples, for the span variance we have more than 5.5K.

Model comparison

We will use LOOIC to compare model fit, as described in the paper.

In [8]:
# plot model LOOIC to see which model fits best
g_comparison, comparison = pmu.compare([model_span_intercept,
                                        model_span_task
                                       ], ic='LOO')
plt.savefig('figures/digit_span_model_comparison.pdf')
plt.savefig('figures/digit_span_model_comparison.png', dpi=600)
display(comparison)
LOO pLOO dLOO weight SE dSE shape_warn
Intercept + task_z + 1|pp 442.39 64.49 0 1 20.96 0 1
Intercept + 1|pp 528.77 39.78 86.38 0 20 13.35 1

The task model is clearly performing better, so that is the model we will extract intercepts from.

Plotting selected model traces

As an additional check, we will plot the posterior traces for the selected model. Ideally these look unimodal and roughly normal. The plots on the righthand side should look like fuzzy caterpillars.

In [9]:
g_traces = pm.traceplot(model_span_task.backend.trace)
plt.savefig('figures/digit_span_model_traces.png', dpi=600)

Extracting participant intercept modes

We will now extract and store the posterior modes of the participant intercepts so we can use them to model reading scores.

In [10]:
pps = df_span['pp'].unique()
pp_nums = [f'1|pp__{i}' for i in range(len(pps))]
df_intercepts = pmu.summary(model_span_task.backend.trace).loc[pp_nums]
df_intercepts['pp'] = np.sort(pps)

df_uncorrected = df_span.groupby('pp', as_index=False).mean().rename(columns={'span': 'raw_span_mean'})
df_intercepts = df_intercepts[['pp', 'mode']].rename(columns={'mode': 'span_intercept'})
df_intercepts = df_intercepts.merge(df_uncorrected[['pp', 'reading_z', 'raw_span_mean']],
                                    left_on='pp', right_on='pp').reset_index()
